  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Understanding customer business activities\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting\n- Monitoring transactions\n- Reporting unusual or suspicious financial activities\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n\n3. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer identification information\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\n4. Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Conducting employee training\n- Establishing compliance oversight mechanisms\n\n5. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) regulations\n- Adhering to Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Complying with international anti-money laundering standards\n\n6. Risk Assessment\n- Conducting periodic risk assessments\n- Identifying high-risk customers or transactions\n- Implementing enhanced monitoring for high-risk scenarios\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal prosecution.",
